<pre class="bz_comment_text">Hono allows a gateway to subscribe for command messages that are directed at a device that the gateway may act on behalf of.
For this, an authenticated gateway, connected via AMQP or MQTT, includes the corresponding device id in the receiver link address or subscription topic.

The issue is, that the AMQP and MQTT adapters currently don't check, whether the gateway is actually allowed to create such a command subscription for the given device id.

That means that any authenticated device (not necessarily a gateway) can use a different device id of the same tenant in the command receiver link address or subscription topic and thereby receive commands for that other device (of the same tenant).

The relevant check of the given device id (verifying that the authenticated device id is contained in the via-gateways of the given device) is only done when sending the &quot;ttd&quot; event message as part of the subscription request. Although there is an error there (rightfully so), the preceding command subscription is still kept in place. The issue doesn't exist for HTTP and CoAP adapters because the error sending the &quot;ttd&quot; message will abort the request and close the command subscription.</pre>
    </div>

